# Yulin Zhang, 2026.2.24

This folder contains all scripts used to run SINGER on real data. In the text below, we would show how these scripts are used by breaking down the steps.

## Step 1: make input files

SINGER takes VCF files with only biallelic sites as inputs. Here I am showing a pipeline for handling 1000 Genomes phased VCF files.

```
# Get all the YRI individuals from sample information
less -S 1000g_sample.tsv | grep "YRI" | cut -f 1 > YRI.sample
# Subset the original VCF to maintain only biallelic sites & YRI samples
bcftools view --samples-file YRI.sample -m 2 -M 2 -v snps ${1000g_vcf} -Oz -o 1000g_YRI_chr1.vcf.gz
```

If one wants to polarize the SNPs using an ancestral genome, the following command could be used.

```
# Polarize the VCF from ref / alt to ancestral / derived; note this script requires the input VCF to be gziped
python polarize_vcf.py -vcf 1000g_YRI.vcf.gz -fasta ${ancestral_file} -output 1000g_YRI_chr1_polarized.vcf
```

## Step 2: make SLURM job scripts for running SINGER

As recommanded by SINGER, to speed up the runs, we could break a long chromosome into small genomic chunks of 2 Mbp and run SINGER on them in parallel. Here we prepared `singer_base.sh` which is the base script specifying the parameters used in SINGER runs. We used `produce_sbatch.py` to produce SLURM scripts for each genomic chunk.

```
> python produce_sbatch.py -h
usage: produce_sbatch.py [-h] --chunk-size CHUNK_SIZE --sbatch-base SBATCH_BASE --nposterior NPOSTERIOR
                         --singer-outpref SINGER_OUTPREF --output OUTPUT --sites SITES --chromosome CHROMOSOME

Generate sbatch job files for singer submission. Please modify exclude regions in the code.

optional arguments:
  -h, --help            show this help message and exit
  --chunk-size CHUNK_SIZE
                        size of each chunk
  --sbatch-base SBATCH_BASE
                        base sbatch file
  --nposterior NPOSTERIOR
                        number of posterior samples you want from SINGER
  --singer-outpref SINGER_OUTPREF
                        singer output prefix
  --output OUTPUT       prefix for output files of this script
  --sites SITES         sites file for the chromosome
  --chromosome CHROMOSOME
                        chromosome number (int)
```

Here is an example usage of the script

```
# Generate .sites file, which contains positions of all SNPs in the VCF file
bcftools query -f "%POS\n" 1000g_YRI_chr1_polarized.vcf > 1000g_YRI_chr1_polarized.sites

# Get all SLURM scripts for SINGER runs at different genomic chunks on chr1
# this would preduce sbatch_files/yri_chr1_*.sbatch and sbatch_files/yri_chr1_posterior_*.txt
python produce_sbatch.py --chunk-size 2000000 --sbatch-base singer_base.sh --nposterior 300 --singer-outpref /path/to/output/folder/yri_chr1 --output sbatch_files/yri_chr1 --sites 1000g_YRI_chr1_polarized.sites --chromosome 1
```

The output files above would be in the directory `sbatch_files`, containing files with names `yri_chr1_*.sbatch` (SLURM scripts one could directly `sbatch` submit to run, should have (genome_length / `--chunk-size`) number of files) and `yri_chr1_posterior_*.txt` (used to convert SINGER raw outputs to tskit format, should have the same number of files as the `--nposterior` input above).

To submit jobs to SLURM and run SINGER, example code

```
# Submit jobs to SLURM to run SINGER
cd sbatch_files
for i in `ls *sbatch`
do
    sbatch $i
done
```

## Step 3: convert SINGER outputs to tskit format

A SINGER run with the output prefix `yri_chr1_${j}` would produce `yri_chr1_${j}_nodes_${i}.txt`, `yri_chr1_${j}_branches_${i}.txt`, `yri_chr1_${j}_muts_${i}.txt`, `yri_chr1_${j}_recombs_${i}.txt` where $i denotes the posterior tree sequence ID (0-299 in this case for the code above), $j denotes the genomic chunk (for example, 0 could indicate the region chr1:0-2000000). As noted in the previous step, we break the genome into 2 Mbp chunks, so for chr1 we would have around 114 chunks in total (excluding not accessible regions). We want to combine these 114 chunks (all $j) to one full chr1 for every posterior tree sequence ID (per $i).

The `merge_ARGs.py` script takes in one of the `yri_chr1_posterior_{0..299}.txt` files as input and output one `.tsz` file per run.

```
# This would produce 300 posterior tree sequences sampled from SINGER for the whole chr1
for i in {0..299}
do
    python merge_ARGs.py --file_table sbatch_files/yri_chr1_posterior_${i}.txt --output yri_chr1_${i}.tsz
done
```
